To understand the effect of CDs on the electrochemical behavior of the electrodes, we conducted EIS characterizations. The equivalent circuit and Nyquist plots of RGO and RC-x samples are given in Fig. 8
                     . The equivalent circuit shows the electrolyte resistance (Re), charge transfer resistance (Rct), electrical double layer capacitance (C) and Warburg impedance (Zw), which corresponds to the semicircle intercept on the real axis at high frequency region, the semicircle at middle frequency region and the straight line at low frequency region, respectively [30,64,68,73]. The Re (~5.8 Ω) and the corresponding time constant τo (the inverse of frequency at 45° in the Bode phase plots (Fig. S11)), seen in both RGO and RC-x samples, indicate similar wettability and intrinsic resistance [11,81]. The identified values of Rct (Table 2
                     ) confirm the above results. RGO shows a higher charge transfer resistance of 15.7 Ω in comparison with RC-x electrodes, which is mainly due to aggregation of graphene nanosheets in the sample, leading to low conductivity for RGO [17,81]. EIS measurements reveal that the RC-21 composite exhibits the lowest charge transfer resistance of 6.4 Ω; however, for higher amount of CD (50 wt%) in RGO, the Rct increased to 7.5 Ω. This may have resulted from the increased load of non-conductive oxygen/nitrogen functional groups, and consequent decline in conductivity [29,64].

The diffusion coefficients calculated from the slope of the plot between Re(Z) and inverse square root of the angular frequency (Fig. 9
                     ) are listed in Table 3
                     . The DH+ values support the above CV, GCD and EIS results. The RC-21 composite exhibits the highest proton diffusion coefficient of 17.27 × 10−18 cm2 s−1 compared to that of RGO (1.07 × 10−18 cm2 s−1), which indicates that the CDs enable fast ion diffusion from the electrolyte to the electrode, leading to excellent capacitance retention for RC-x samples compared to RGO.
